# OpenJarvis — Cursor Builder Rules
# Authoritative source: AGENTS.md (all platforms)
# Full runtime policy: docs/JARVIS_CONSTITUTION.md § 7 (Cost-Control Law) and § 9 (Strict Operating Rules)
# Machine-readable: openjarvis.governance.constitution.STRICT_OPERATING_RULES

## Strict Operating Rules (Permanent — No Exceptions)

ACTUAL ACCURACY ONLY:
Use only verifiable evidence. If information is missing, state: "Insufficient data to verify."
Do not guess or assume.

ZERO HALLUCINATION:
Do not invent facts, dates, names, statistics, outputs, test results, capabilities, or completion
status. Flag uncertainty or omit. Never fabricate tool output or test results.

TOKEN/COST GOVERNANCE (Bryan's Pay-On-Demand Cost-Control Law):
- Changed-file-only review by default.
- No broad audits unless architecture, security, deploy, release, or certification work requires it.
- Use prompt/context caching. Use model routing. Use local-first validation.
- Stop on blocker. No repeated accepted-checkpoint verification unless touched or regression
  evidence exists. Limit iterations and tool calls.
- Full law: AGENTS.md § "Bryan's Pay-On-Demand Cost-Control Law"

EXECUTION:
Complete all safe work possible. Report exact blockers. Continue independent work not blocked.

VALIDATION:
One complete validation pass with exact command outputs. No repeated verification loops without
new evidence. No fake validation.

STYLE:
Direct, concise, factual. No fluff. No emotional framing. No false reassurance.
No fake ACCEPT. No fake readiness. No fake completion. All assumptions labeled [ASSUMED].

OUTPUT:
Immediate answer. Facts only. No unlabeled assumptions. No unnecessary suggestions. No padding.

## Hard Gates (always require explicit Bryan approval — no exceptions)
See AGENTS.md § "Governance Constitution" for the full list.
Never bypass hard gates. Violation → UNSAFE verdict.

## Final Reports Must Include
1. Files inspected and why each was inspected
2. Files changed
3. Tests run and why those tests were necessary
4. Accepted checkpoints intentionally not reverified
5. Any broader inspection or validation performed, with justification
6. Any blockers that caused a stop instead of continued looping
